  "prompt": "Are there international laws against money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several international laws and conventions aimed at combating money laundering. Here are some of the most important ones:\n\n*   **The United Nations Convention Against Illicit Traffic in Narcotic Drugs and Psychotropic Substances (1988):** This convention was one of the first international instruments to address money laundering, focusing specifically on the proceeds of drug trafficking. It requires signatory countries to criminalize the laundering of drug money and to cooperate in international investigations and prosecutions.\n\n*   **The United Nations Convention Against Transnational Organized Crime (2000):** This convention broadened the scope of international anti-money laundering efforts to include the proceeds of all serious crimes, not just drug trafficking. It requires countries to criminalize the laundering of the proceeds of crime and to implement measures for the confiscation of such proceeds.\n\n*   **The International Convention for the Suppression of the Financing of Terrorism (1999):** While focused on terrorism financing, this convention also contributes to the broader anti-money laundering framework by requiring countries to criminalize the financing of terrorism and to implement measures to prevent and suppress such financing.\n\n*   **Financial Action Task Force (FATF) Recommendations:** While not a treaty or convention, the FATF Recommendations are the global standard for combating money laundering and terrorist financing. These recommendations provide a comprehensive framework of measures that countries should implement, covering areas such as criminalization of money laundering, customer due diligence, record-keeping, and international cooperation. FATF monitors countries' compliance with these recommendations and publishes reports identifying jurisdictions with weak anti-money laundering regimes.\n\nThese international laws and standards provide a framework for countries to enact their own domestic laws and regulations to combat money laundering. They also promote international cooperation in the investigation and prosecution of money laundering offenses.",
